{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c6589bff-97a7-43db-880f-4fdc7da961bb","content":"Here's my analysis:\n\n## Diagnosis\n\nThe project file is minimal and clean — there's nothing in `SlowCliBuilds.csproj` causing slowness. The developer report correctly identifies the root cause: **MSBuild process startup and project re-evaluation on every `dotnet build` invocation**. Visual Studio avoids this because it keeps a long-lived MSBuild server process in memory.\n\n## Recommendations (most to least impactful)\n\n### 1. Use `dotnet watch build` for the inner loop\nKeeps MSBuild alive and watches for changes — no repeated startup cost:\n```\ndotnet watch build\n```\n\n### 2. Enable the MSBuild Build Server\n.NET 8 supports a persistent MSBuild server (similar to VS). Enable it:\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\ndotnet build          # first build warms the server\ndotnet build          # subsequent builds reuse it — much faster\n```\nOr set it permanently in a `Directory.Build.rsp` file at the repo root:\n```\n-nodeReuse:true\n```\n\n### 3. Verify node reuse isn't disabled\nCheck that this env var is **not** set (some CI configs leak it into dev shells):\n```bash\necho $MSBUILDDISABLENODEREUSE   # should be empty or 0\n```\nIf it's `1`, unset it for local dev work.\n\n### 4. For larger solutions, add `ProduceReferenceAssembly`\nNot needed for this single-project case, but for multi-project solutions add to `Directory.Build.props`:\n```xml\n<ProduceReferenceAssembly>true</ProduceReferenceAssembly>\n```\nThis lets downstream projects skip recompilation when only method bodies change.\n\n---\n\n**TL;DR**: The project itself is fine. The 2–4s overhead is MSBuild cold-start. Use `dotnet watch build` or enable the MSBuild server (`DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1`) to match VS performance.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bae060c2-90aa-4a26-8412-6f2fe81e96a1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer reports that `dotnet build` from the CLI is slow for incremental builds (2-4 seconds even when nothing changed), while Visual Studio rebuilds nearly instantly.\n\nThe key insight here is about **why** Visual Studio is faster: VS uses a long-lived MSBuild server process (the \"design-time build\" and build server), which keeps MSBuild nodes warm in memory. When you run `dotnet build` from the CLI, it:\n\n1. Starts a new `dotnet` process\n2. Loads the MSBuild SDK\n3. Evaluates the project graph\n4. Checks for incremental build (skips compilation)\n\n\n5. Exits\n\nThat startup and evaluation overhead accounts for the 2-4 seconds, even though the actual build work is skipped. The solution is to enable MSBuild's server mode—available in .NET 6+ through the `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER` environment variable or `-server` flag—which keeps the build process alive between invocations. I should also check if `MSBUILDDISABLENODEREUSE=1` is set, since that would disable node reuse and force the same slow startup each time. The MSBuild Server is enabled by default in .NET 8 in certain scenarios, though the environment variable might still be useful for explicit control. The most practical recommendations would focus on enabling the server mode, using `dotnet watch` to avoid repeated process startup, and potentially adding reference assembly generation to reduce downstream recompilation overhead. The real solution here isn't tweaking the project file—it's managing the MSBuild process lifecycle. I need to make sure node reuse is enabled and recommend the practical tools like `dotnet watch` and the MSBuild server to eliminate that startup overhead.","outputTokens":1491,"requestId":"780A:28BCD7:7F3C2F7:8D67524:69EABD7F"},"id":"990511e2-2286-4804-87d2-60fe57c4a0ec","timestamp":"2026-04-24T00:47:27.115Z","parentId":"79402189-adfe-47e7-92cc-cf19f677f780"}
